<Layout title="About">
  <div class="page-head">
    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>About Econschool</h1>
    <p class="standfirst">
      Why this exists, who makes it, and how to reach us.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Why Econschool exists</h2>
  <p>
    Econschool is built to serve students, because we care about economics. The aim
    is a high-quality, lasting learning resource for current and future economics
    students — one that holds to mathematical rigor, prefers depth to virality, and
    stays useful whether ten students use it or ten thousand.
  </p>
  <p>
    The free material — lectures, problems, tools — is the core of that purpose.
    The paid program and workshops exist for students who want live teaching and
    structure; they fund the rest, but they are not the point of it.
  </p>

  <h2>Who makes it</h2>
  <p>
    Econschool is run by <strong>Amit Goyal</strong>, an economics coach and
    academic specialist affiliated with NYU Abu Dhabi, with a background at the
    Indian Statistical Institute and the Delhi School of Economics. His work
    centres on microeconomic theory and economics education.
  </p>
  <p>
    The LaTeX presentations behind the video lectures are created together with
    <strong>Nidhi Jain</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>How we work</h2>
  <p>
    Everything follows a few fixed principles: full mathematical working, always;
    plain English, no showing off; and consistent visual conventions — the colors
    in our diagrams mean the same thing in every postcard, slide, and video, so
    what you learn to read once, you can read everywhere.
  </p>

  <h2 id="contact">Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Questions about the program, the workshops, or anything on this site are
    welcome.
  </p>
